segments.text: Besides mapping, how about programs?
Were there any industrial programs that you instituted?
No.
Shortly after I got here, I realized that this was essentially a fire outfit.
Nothing else really counted.
Sort of piddled around with a nursery, too.
I thought, well, what do we need here in the organization is a man who knows something about silviculture.
And, of course, I was biased about that because that was one of the subjects I taught at LSU.
So I contacted a man who at one time worked with me on a project over in Louisiana by the name of Vaux, who later became
head of the School of Forestry at the University of California at Berkeley.
And I asked him whether he could suggest someone who might be interested in coming to the South, who has had a good basis in silviculture and plant physiology.
He recommended somebody.
We had an interview.
He was employed.
And that's how we got started.
I'd say one of my principal accomplishments here, research in tree improvement.
Okay, now this is later, because you said a while ago, you know, in initial parts you got rid of a kind of a useless silvicultural program.
And so what, then you waited until you had more money in your budget to be able to operate this time?
Well, got a little more money, and I got enough money to employ this fellow as a silviculturist.
Now, he was in the management department.
He wasn't...
Still no silvicultural research.
No, no.
As a matter of fact, there still isn't any silvicultural research per se.
There is research in tree improvement in the forest management department.
Now, you say I'm nitpicking?
No, no.
I can understand it, though.
Okay.
I think.
Because with a very limited...
and the Texas Forest Service has, it should be engaged in only that sort of research that isn't obtainable elsewhere.
And this was the first research in tree improvement in the whole South.
As a matter of fact, almost in the whole nation.
The only other place that it was being done was on a very limited scale in the Lake States and out in California.
The Nelson, I mean the Eddy Tree Breeding Station.
Maybe you'll run across that or have, but... No, I have avoided, for the most part, real technical things that I don't understand.
Okay.

I've avoided them because if I run across it, the only thing that I can ever read that I've read about that was of any research value was done by accident, and it was planting slash pines in 1926, and lo and behold, those things grew fast, and they noticed it, and were able somehow to convince industry.
I guess...
I don't know how they did it.
I don't have enough information to tell them.
They must have brought them in there and said, look, these things grow fast.
And somebody tried them.
Well, there were experimental plantings down in the Siki State Forest.
Yes, in 1926 those first plantings were made.
And I've seen pictures, and they grew very fast.
I've got them in my yard.
They grow fast.
I have no doubt about it.
They shouldn't be planted here.
You're abusing nature when you plant a pine tree here.
I know.
Well, all the roots are on top of the ground.
One of these days it's going to fall on the house.
Okay.
It'll get even with me.
But evidently the things caught on.
Yeah, it is.
And they're getting away from Slash Pie now because it's, oh, this is a technical aspect.
Yeah, well, it was an interest and it caught on.
Okay.
Do you have any other questions?
One, no, I don't have a whole lot.
If that's what you saw, well, yeah, one more, one quick one.
What was the South Central Interstate Forest Fire Protection Compact?
Well, that was an arrangement whereby we could call on adjoining states for assistance because we had an acute forest fire situation and because of liabilities
one state agency would be most reluctant to dispatch anybody to an adjoining state because of liability in case of injury.
And that's why it was set up, created, so that there would be no reluctance for Texas men to go into Louisiana or Arkansas and vice versa for assistance.
Did you all ever do that?
Yeah.
We used the compact in a few cases, but
Now we have all gotten to the point where we're large enough so that we can take care of practically any situation that develops.
Did you set this up?
Or were you involved in setting it up?
I was involved in setting it up, yeah.
Where did this come about?
Is this jawboning with the other guys and decided we needed to do it?
Well, see there's a National Association of State Foresters, has been for a long time.
And I first learned about it because they had what was known as the New England Compact,
The U.S. Forest Service, I think, was responsible for organizing that compact up there in the New England states.
Well, that was a good idea, and some of us thought it had application down there.
So we decided to create one here.
Do you remember what date that was set up?
Well, I can merely give you an approximation.
The office would have a record on this.
I would say about...
I don't remember.
Okay.
I was just curious about that.
One last thing that just dawned on me and I wanted to ask about the advisory committee.
Was this done in any other states?
I don't think so.
So you innovated it?
It's an innovation, I think.
Okay.
I just wondered where you were drawing on past experience.
Well, you see in other places there's a
Arkansas, for example, has a forestry commission where industry is represented on this commission.
They have a similar situation in Louisiana or did.
Oh, I see.
Okay, okay.
So that's, yeah, that's very nice.
That's a good point.
Okay, so it gets industry back into the picture again that way without the commission.
Right.
Marvelous.
In these meetings that you have with the advisory committee,
Did they tell you what they wanted?
Sometimes.
I wouldn't say that it was particularly revolutionary, but it did this.
It established the fact that the Texas Forest Service was interested in establishing communication with industry.
Because I had gotten a complaint from one of the lumbermen, well, we don't know what the Texas Forest Service is doing.
And so you could sit down and say, this, fellas, is what we can do, or this is what we can do for you?
Yeah.
This is what we can't do?
Yeah.
Also, this was a means of mobilizing some legislative input.
I don't know if you...
A form of lobbying, you can say.
Certainly, because these men had their legislators, didn't they?
Sure.
You've got a big business going.
And I'm sure this was a big help in getting any programs through that you wanted, or your budget especially.
Don't overlook the fact also that simultaneously with my coming here,
the Texas forest industry had a representative on the board of directors in the form of Al Cudlip.
Yes, that's in this.
And I think this is some important point I've got to include in this, is that when Cudlip came, it almost seems like...
You were lucky of coming at the right time.
Yeah, right.
I got a break there.
I have no reluctance in admitting that.
Suddenly that somebody was interested in you doing well.
He thought he was going to have more influence directly on the Texas Forest Service than he ever did because Gib Dilchrist disillusioned him in a hurry on that point.
Did he get rid of Gib?
Oh, no.
He didn't help to get rid of Gib?
No, I don't think so.
Later on they got together all right.
But Al recognized that he shouldn't be messing directly with the Texas Forest Service.
He withdrew.
I think Gibb merely told him how the cow ate the cabbage and that's all that was to it.
I can see that.
Did they leave you alone?
Did the university or the system leave you alone?
Sure did.
Is there not a good thing and a bad thing in that?
It had its strengths.
It's nice not to be bothered.
Yeah.
I say this, it may sound like boasting, but it isn't really.
In the presence of other people, D.W. Williams said several times, the best thing that I ever did was leave Al alone.
Had he left the others alone?
No.
He had not?
One reason was he didn't know a damn thing about Forrester.
And he wasn't much interested in learning.
He didn't much care.
He's an agriculturalist.
He's what?
He was an agriculturalist.
Well, he was more of a stock man.
Well, still, that's agriculture.
Yeah.
And I'm not sure agriculture has any real understanding of forestry.
No, it doesn't.
You know, Dean Shepardson, when he was here, he didn't want to have a darn thing to do with forestry.
That's good and bad.
Well, it is bad because had he created
a Department of Forestry here in the College of Agriculture, we wouldn't be in the situation we are today where the Forest Science Department is just sort of limping along.
It's just sort of tolerated.
Because had that department been set up here, the one over at Stephen F. Austin would not have been established.
And I attribute that all to Charlie Shepardson's indifference.
It's amazing.
EJ Kyle promised the legislature that if we got a state forester, we'd have a department of forestry.
Well, that was never created.
And he never did it.
Did you help create the one hand?
No.
You didn't have anything to do with it?
I more or less dragged my feet on it.
Yes, I said I thought it would be a good idea.
And I dragged my feet on it because I had a divided opinion on it.
In the first place, this is where it belonged.
In the second place...
there was this department in existence over at Stephen F. Austin.
It had a running start.
Furthermore, it was over there in a forestry environment.
And they still get that flack here from students.
Well, since we can't take any field trips and we don't have to pay for it to get over into the forestry area, well, we're sort of marooned here.
Yeah, I just wondered if you had anything to do with the creation of that thing.
No, I didn't.
I remember this matter was discussed on occasion within the group that D.W. Williams would sometimes get together.
When you left, did you have any input into who your successor would be?
Well, I'll put it this way.
I made a couple of recommendations.
Okay.
But I...
Yes, I had some input.
But you were not allowed to hand-pick your six-pack?
No, no, no, no.
Was Siki allowed to hand-pick white, I wonder?
I have no idea.
Okay, I was just curious about that.
Something told me he could have done that because...
I had this feeling that the Forest Service, I don't know about now, I don't know a whole lot about what's going on right now, was run so much as an independent agency.
It was, I think.
A&M said, that's nice, don't bother us, we won't bother you.
Of course, they didn't get any money out of it.
A little.
Well, not a whole lot, but it's an interesting setup.
It's a very interesting setup.
Now, one more thing you asked me.
What would I like to take credit for while I was here?
Yeah.
Putting some order in it and initiating this tree improvement work, which has a damn good record.
And this fellow Zobel that I brought in here, he has become...
WORLD AUTHORITY.
HE DIDN'T STAY HERE BECAUSE HE COULDN'T ATTRACT GRADUATE STUDENTS BECAUSE IT WASN'T THE FOREST SCIENCE DEPARTMENT.
WELL, THE OTHER THING IS THAT I WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR PUTTING IN THIS NURSERY THAT WAS LOCATED WHERE IT WAS DURING THE PERIOD WHEN
The Department of Agriculture financed the establishment of nurseries to reforest land that had been thrown out of production because of contraction of agricultural commodity production.
Is this the Magnolia?
That's right.
Later became the Magnolia Springs.
Yeah, this is a nursery.
But this was later converted into a seed orchard, Magnolia Springs Seed Orchard.
It's all a big seed orchard now.
Who was Charlie Heitman?
Do you recall?
No.
Okay.
I'm just curious.
I happened to find an extra one of those in my files.
I have the chancellor's office files from that period.
There's just not much in there.
I wouldn't think so.
There's not.
I appreciate this interview.
You've given me much more than I can ever need.
Have I given you everything?
Oh, I'll probably think of something later, but I can't imagine more than...
